My mom is Gangsta. On Friday during the Ice Storm she slipped in her back yard and fractured her hip. She was alone at the time. She called my dad and he got home called the ambulance and took care of her while they waited for them to arrive. She underwent successful surgery on Saturday the nurses are shocked she is doing so good and is expected to go home tomorrow. 
This is the first year I can ever remember not spending Christmas with my kids and parents. They requested instead of visiting her in the hospital today to come over tomorrow to help get her settled in.

I think this might be my favorite picture of the kids and I. This is when I lived in LA and I would fly to Seattle every month for my weekend visit. I didn’t have much money in those days and the plane tickets weren’t cheap but this picture captures the pure joy, love and excitement between my kids and I. They are all grown  now 25 (almost 26) and 24. I really miss these days and often dream that they were still my little ones.
I was a child, I blinked my eyes and I was a father I blinked again and I was an old man. #family #father #kids #love

In honor of International Women’s Day I wanted to share one of my favorite paintings “Chicana in College” the painting is part of a series entitled “Norman Rockwell in post racial America”, where I re-envisioned Rockwell paintings and flipped them in a contemporary lens with people of color as the subject. In the original Rockwell painting, entitled Willie Gillis goes to college, It showed a young man returning from World War II in his college dorm with his war memorabilia on the wall while he reads a book in the windowsill. this made me think what would a Chicanas war memorabilia be? I envisioned her protest posters, and books. one of things I love best about this painting is how it resonates with so many women. I often hear people tell me how it reminds them of themselves or their sisters or their daughters or other people they know. It seems everyone sees someone in the painting. #internationalwomensday #women #mujeres #chingona #chingonas #oilpainting #jakeprendezart #art #painting #vivalamujer #chicana #chicanaincollege

I’ll be displaying for the West Seattle Art Walk. Head to @meet_mara_at_compass to see my artwork tomorrow from 5 to 8pm for the @wsartwalk. Jake Prendez is a Seattle based Chicano artist and the owner/co-director of the Nepantla Cultural Arts Gallery on the border of West Seattle and White Center. He also exhibits his art and lectures across the country.

Jake’s work is an amalgamation of his life experiences. It is an expression of his Chicano background, his life lived between Los Angeles & Seattle, it represents love & heartbreak, oppression and resilience, laughter and tears. His oil paintings and digital artwork are created with a specific focus on themes relating to Chicanx and Indigenous culture, social justice, pop culture, and satire.

https://www.jakeprendez.com/

A Chicano Art Legend in the Pacific Northwest has sadly passed away. Alfredo Arreguin was a titan yet still warm and welcoming! He referred to me as his good friend “Jack Prendez” lol. We were honored to host his amazing paintings in our Latinx in the Northwest exhibition. I also got to share the stage with him at the Seattle Art Museum to Talk about Chicano Art. He and his Wife Susan graciously welcomed Judy and I to there home and gave us a tour of their studios. We are shocked and saddened by his passing but so grateful that we will have his gorgeous and vibrant paintings to keep us engaged. Our deepest condolences go out to Alfredo’s wife Susan and family. @alfredarreg

Post 1/3 Un Gran Noche con Mi Amor!
We had a great time celebrating at the opening of “The Gallery” at the Paramount!! It was wonderful to see so many gente having a good time!! Thank you so much to Marisol and all the folks from @stgpresents for believing in the work that Nepantla is doing and inviting us to curate this show! 
We want to thank the amazing artists on display @joserodriguez3rd @mexistential_dread @perikotheartist @teresaaangela @hellomelendez @raquelitagm @jakeprendez and Cecilia Alvarez. Thank you for trusting us to curate this one of a kind, year long exhibition highlighting Chicana/o Mexican artistas! 
It was a puro pinche pari!! We’ll bet that this the first time the Paramount has had so much firme Chicana/o Art in the gallery, Cumbias playing in the lobby thanks to @esepax and a damn Lowrider in the Lobby!! 
Cultura es la cura! There is a Latinx art movement happening in Seattle that is going virtual unnoticed. The Nepantla Cultural Arts Gallery and events like this are changing that and showing there IS an audience and a community craving cultura! #nepantlaculturalartsgallery #paramount #art #chicanoart #chicanaart #chicano #chicana #chicanx #mexican #art #arte #painting #oilpainting #acrylicpainting #seattle #paramounttheatre #stgpresents #gente #love

They just keep ignoring us. Reposted from @nbclatino 
Most of the seminal events impacting U.S. Latino history are not a subject of study in high schools across the country, according to a new report by Johns Hopkins Institute for Education Policy and UnidosUS.

The study found that 87% of key Latino topics were either not covered in U.S. history textbooks or were mentioned in just five or fewer sentences.

"Only 28 of 222 important topics were covered well, leaving out many aspects of the Mexican-American War, the Spanish-American War, the U.S. acquisition of Puerto Rico," and other events, according to a release on the report.

I’ve been painting for 16 years now. I thought it would be cool to show the progression of my artwork in the next several days. Today I’m posting paintings from 2007-2010. I was still living in LA at this time and working on my masters in Chicana/o Studies at Cal State Northridge. I was mostly painting with acrylic and some spray paint from time to time. I was really into stencil style art and painting my favorite bands at the time like Johnny Cash, the Beatles or The Clash. 2007-2010 was The birth of my art. At this point it was just a hobby and I don’t think I was exhibiting any of my work yet. Around this time is when I met @theartofsketch and @deadmundo and we would start to do some really cool shows, Art walks and events together. #jakeprendezart #art #chicanoart #acrylicpainting

I’ve been painting for 16 years now. I thought it would be cool to show the progression of my artwork in the next several days. Today I’m posting paintings from 2011-2014. I was still in my 30’s and working as a College recruiter for CSUN full time. Painting was still a hobby. My skills and style began to develop during this period. I was moving away from the stencil style work and developing my own style. I was doing more acrylic portraits. It was a time of great change. While my art was on the rise my personal life took a major hit. My life collapsed but began to rebuild during this period. I got divorced, My mom got really sick, my mentor died, i was trying to be a good Dad, I was trying to finish a thesis paper for my masters in Chicana/o Studies and I was trying to do a Chicano comedy/satire zine and still work my 9 to 5. Yeah I over did it and went into a deep depression. 
I also started getting out into the community more, hosting art shows with Sketch and Deadmundo. We created a pretty Dope Chicana/o Art community. We were like familia. My artwork was also beginning to get a little more attention. I was hanging with amazingly talented artists, activists, musicians, poets, fashionistas, writers etc. it was like A Harlem renaissance in East LA. A new Jake was being born and I don’t think my friends knew how much I needed them and how much I appreciated their support during this time. #jakeprendezart #art #acrylicpainting #painting #chicano #chicanoart #Chicana #friends #eastla #bloodinbloodout #cheech #labamba #bobmorales #salcastro #harrypotter #snape #starwars

I’ve been painting for 16 years now. I thought it would be cool to show the progression of my artwork in the next several days. Today I’m posting paintings from 2015-2019 “The Bounce Back Years”. 2015 was my Last year in LA before I moved to Seattle to be closer to my kids. This is a period a massive growth as an artist. I moved from acrylic paints to oil paints. My paintings were more concept and story driven. I did a lot of painting series during this time like my Mujeres Fuertes Series, my Cultural Resilience series, my dulces series and I started my Norman Rockwell in Post Racial America series. 
Although I still greatly miss LA, the move to Seattle was really good to me. I met my Fiancé @js3luvs , we started The Nepantla Cultural Arts Gallery, I began getting more attention as an artist and community advocate. I began doing more lectures and exhibitions around the country. These are the beginning of the good years. 😊 #jakeprendezart #artist #art #oilpainting #acrylicpainting #painting #chicano #chicana #chicanoart #love

I’ve been painting for 16 years now. I thought it would be cool to show the progression of my artwork in the next several days. Today I’m posting paintings from 2020-2023. We made it to 2023. This is the final post “The Rise of Nepantla”. With the success of the Nepantla Cultural Arts Gallery much of my time and focus has gone to the gallery. Running the gallery with all the monthly exhibitions, writing grants, host community events, workshops, book readings, doing lectures, panels and serving on arts boards is a 25 hour a day job for Judy and I. It’s exhausting but also pretty damn amazing to see the great impact our work is having in the Community. Even though I’m blessed to have an amazing partner to run all this with me it has really taken its toll on my painting time. I use to do about 12 paintings a year, now I’m doing about 6 art pieces a year. Even though my output is down my artwork continues progressing and grow. My painting are getting recognized and I’m getting noticed as an artist and community advocate.
So what’s in store for the future? How do I find a way to increase my painting time? How do Judy and I expand Nepantla? How do I do all of this and still find quality time with my family? Let’s hope I find the answers and have more great news in the next 4 years! #jakeprendez #jakeprendezart #art #oilpainting #painting #chicano #chicana #chicanx #chicanoart #seattle #whitecenter #love #amor #luchador #diadelosmuertos #aoc #ancestors

“Piñata Party” 60”x48” oil & acrylic on canvas by Jake Prendez 2023. How many saw me working on this painting at @nepantlaculturalarts 
After almost a year I finally finished my newest painting modeled by (left to right) Isabel, Catalina, Joaquin, Leo and Cassandra (our sobrinos and our daughter Cata). The painting is more than a typical piñata scene it is part super hero tribute (Joaquin in the middle in a heroic proud pose), part social realism ( I am working on series that shows the everyday person as heroic, “super” with value  or agency minus the cape) and part magical realism ( the mass explosion of candy).

In honor of Indigenous peoples day, Here are the 4 paintings from my "Cultural Resilience: We still Exist" series. Our people and our culture is not extinct. We still survive and thrive. The paintings are about exploring our roots and the way we look at ourselves. The ways in which our indigenous culture has survived. Our culture survives in our cooking, they way we dance, it is in our mannerisms, our language, our beliefs, in the ways we embrace our elders and raise our children. We never left, we are not an extinct people. We are still here and we maintain and continue to create culture everyday. Happy Indigenous People’s Day. #indigenouspeoplesday #indigenous #jakeprendezart #oilpainting #painting #chicanoart #indigenousart #nativeamerican #chicano #chicana

Found some old drawings of mine from my teenage years (93-96). This is when I was told by Art teachers and old (non-brown) artists that my art was “too ethnic and too gangster”. This is about when I gave up Art. 
It wouldn’t be another 10 years before I picked up a paint brush in Yreina Cervantes class and fell in love with Art all over again. 
I really wish someone had seen what I was trying to create back then and nurtured my artwork rather than destroy my soul. If so there wouldn’t have been this 10 year gap when I wasn’t creating Art. I would probably be a better artist with 10 more years of experience. For this reason I try to work with youth in the arts especially young Chicana/o artists who are probably hearing the same thing. 
Despite what they said, there is a place for Chicana/o art in this world, I am living proof.

Myself and @rcxr.art were hired by the White Center Food Bank to create a large mural early this year. After conducting multiple community input sessions, designing the mural, and multiple constructions delays, we were finally able to get to work at the end of November. We finally finished this week. I’m really proud of this mural. It’s the first mural project that I have led (co-led with Rafa). I want to thank Jefferson Rose and the rest folks at the White Center Food Bank for trusting us with the mural. I also want to thank all the artists that supported Rafa And myself such as @js3luvs @josuelopezquiroz and my daughter Talia. You can now go check it out for yourself on 16th Ave in White Center in between KFC and Auto Zone. #jakeprendezart #art #mural #seattle #Whitecenter #whitecenterfoodbank #chicanoart #community

Nepantla Cultural Arts Gallery were invited by our neighbors at HPIC to curate an art installation at the Highland Park Improvement Club @hpicseattle . The property is currently under construction and hopes to display community murals once the work is done. 

With our mission to make art an accessible experience for our community, we chose to highlight three local Chicana/o Latine artists : Jake Prendez ( @jakeprendez ), Raquel Garcia ( @raquelitagm ) & Rolando Avila ( @mexistential_dread )
